title.narrative: OUTPUT 1.1 ECD: QUALITY HEALTHCARE, NUTRITION, WASH

description.narrative: 1.1 By 2022, the Health, Nutrition and WASH service delivery systems provide quality healthcare, nutrition and WASH interventions for pregnant women and children under 5 from the most vulnerable families, which contributes to Child Health, Maternal And Newborn Health, Prevention Of Stunting And Other Forms Of Malnutrition, Sanitation, Treatment Of Severe Acute Malnutrition. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Evaluations, Research And Data, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2022, children under 5 in targeted areas benefit from improved access to quality healthcare and nutrition, protection and development opportunities in their home, care and preschool environments.

description.narrative: UNICEF, with other key stakeholders, outlined a vision to End Child Malnutrition to H.E. the President of Sri Lanka. The portfolio consisting of an abridged version of the State of the World's Children report on why it is imperative to address child malnutrition in Sri Lanka, and the key findings from the Financial Assessment of Nutrition in Sri Lanka. UNICEF also launched a formative research to understand the determinants of infant and young child feeding practices across urban, rural and estate sectors to inform the development of interventions, including social and behavioral change strategies. | Status:Constrained | As-of Date:25/08/2020
